Note:
C Translator Test Suite - Comprehensive testing for C→HIR→C translation

This file provides complete test coverage for:
- C Lexer: Tokenization of C source code
- C Parser: AST construction from tokens
- C Semantic Analysis: Type checking and validation
- C→HIR Translation: AST to HIR conversion
- HIR→C Generation: HIR back to C source
- Round-trip Testing: Verify translation fidelity

Test Coverage:
- Keywords and identifiers
- Operators (arithmetic, logical, bitwise, compound)
- Literals (integers, floats, strings, characters)
- Type declarations (int, float, char, void, pointers, arrays)
- Expressions (binary, unary, call, subscript, member, ternary, sizeof, cast)
- Statements (if, while, for, do-while, switch, return, break, continue, goto, labels)
- Functions (declarations, definitions, parameters, return types)
- Variables (declarations, initializations, arrays, pointers)
- Preprocessor directives
:End Note

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/c/c_lexer.runa" as Lexer
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/c/c_parser.runa" as Parser
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/c/c_semantic.runa" as Semantic
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/c/c_to_hir.runa" as ToHIR
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/backends/c/hir_to_c.runa" as FromHIR
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Test Orchestration
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Top-level driver for the C translator suite. Runs lexer, parser,
semantic, to-HIR, from-HIR, and round-trip checks in dependency
order so failures point at the lowest-level component.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Print banner, call each test_* proc serially. Failures are reported
inline by the assert_* helpers. Returns 1 unconditionally (the suite
does not aggregate; success is signalled by the absence of FAILED
lines in stdout).
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- All test_* procs print "[OK]" lines -> clean suite, return 1
- Any assert_* failure prints "FAILED:" line -> visible in CI output
@End TestCases

Process called "run_all_c_tests" returns Integer:
    Note: Run complete C translator test suite

    proc print_string with "C Translator Test Suite"
    proc print_newline
    proc print_newline

    Note: Lexer tests
    proc test_lexer_keywords
    proc test_lexer_operators
    proc test_lexer_literals
    proc test_lexer_identifiers
    proc test_lexer_comments
    proc test_lexer_preprocessor

    Note: Parser tests
    proc test_parser_expressions
    proc test_parser_statements
    proc test_parser_declarations
    proc test_parser_functions
    proc test_parser_types

    Note: Semantic analysis tests
    proc test_semantic_type_checking
    proc test_semantic_scope_resolution

    Note: Translation tests
    proc test_c_to_hir_translation
    proc test_hir_to_c_generation

    Note: Round-trip tests
    proc test_round_trip_simple
    proc test_round_trip_complex

    proc print_newline
    proc print_string with "All C translator tests completed!"
    proc print_newline

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Lexer Tests
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Verifies the C lexer recognizes the 10 most common C90 keywords in a
single source line. Catches a regression where the keyword table was
truncated or the prefix-match logic misfires (e.g. "return" being
classified as identifier).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Tokenize "int void char float double if else while for return".
Assert token count > 0 and count == 10 (exactly one token per keyword).
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- Input 10 keywords -> 10 tokens
- Keyword table missing entry -> count < 10 -> "Correct number of keyword tokens" fails
- Lexer reads two keywords as one -> count < 10 -> fails
@End TestCases

Process called "test_lexer_keywords" returns Integer:
    Note: Test C keyword tokenization

    proc print_string with "Testing C lexer (keywords)..."
    proc print_newline

    Let source be proc create_string_literal with "int void char float double if else while for return"
    Let lexer be proc create_lexer from Lexer with source
    proc tokenize from Lexer with lexer

    Let tokens be proc get_tokens from Lexer with lexer
    Let token_count be proc size from List with tokens

    Let _kw_ok be token_count is greater than 0
    proc assert_true with _kw_ok, "Keyword tokenization produces tokens"

    Let expected_count be 10
    proc assert_equals with token_count, expected_count, "Correct number of keyword tokens"

    proc destroy_lexer from Lexer with lexer
    proc print_string with "  ✓ Keyword lexer tests passed"
    proc print_newline

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Verifies the C lexer handles arithmetic, comparison, logical,
bitwise, and compound-assignment operators including multi-character
forms (==, !=, <=, >=, &&, ||, ++, --, +=, -=, *=, /=, ->). The
soft "> 20" assertion lets the maximal-munch logic emit either fused
or split tokens.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Tokenize a string containing all the listed operators. Assert token
count > 20.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- Long operator string -> > 20 tokens
- Lexer fails to recognize "&&" as a single token -> may still
  produce > 20 (silent split)
- Lexer collapses too many operators -> count <= 20 ->
  "Operator tokenization produces many tokens" fails
@End TestCases

Process called "test_lexer_operators" returns Integer:
    Note: Test C operator tokenization

    proc print_string with "Testing C lexer (operators)..."
    proc print_newline

    Let source be proc create_string_literal with "+ - * / % = == != < > <= >= && || ! bitwise and | bitwise xor shifted left by shifted right by ++ -- += -= *= /= ->"
    Let lexer be proc create_lexer from Lexer with source
    proc tokenize from Lexer with lexer

    Let tokens be proc get_tokens from Lexer with lexer
    Let token_count be proc size from List with tokens

    Let _op_ok be token_count is greater than 20
    proc assert_true with _op_ok, "Operator tokenization produces many tokens"

    proc destroy_lexer from Lexer with lexer
    proc print_string with "  ✓ Operator lexer tests passed"
    proc print_newline

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Verifies the lexer handles all C literal forms: decimal int (42),
float (3.14), char ('a'), string ("hello"), hex (0xFF), binary
(0b1010), suffixed long (123L), and suffixed unsigned long long
(456ULL). The 8 distinct forms together stress every literal
sub-state in the lexer.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Tokenize a string containing all 8 literal forms. Assert token
count > 7.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- 8 literal forms -> > 7 tokens
- Lexer fails on 0b binary -> count drops below 8
- Lexer rejects ULL suffix -> count drops below 8 or crashes
@End TestCases

Process called "test_lexer_literals" returns Integer:
    Note: Test C literal tokenization

    proc print_string with "Testing C lexer (literals)..."
    proc print_newline

    Let source be proc create_string_literal with "42 3.14 'a' \"hello\" 0xFF 0b1010 123L 456ULL"
    Let lexer be proc create_lexer from Lexer with source
    proc tokenize from Lexer with lexer

    Let tokens be proc get_tokens from Lexer with lexer
    Let token_count be proc size from List with tokens

    Let _lit_ok be token_count is greater than 7
    proc assert_true with _lit_ok, "Literal tokenization produces tokens"

    proc destroy_lexer from Lexer with lexer
    proc print_string with "  ✓ Literal lexer tests passed"
    proc print_newline

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Verifies the lexer accepts the four standard C identifier conventions:
camelCase (myVar), underscore-prefixed (_privateVar), simple camelCase
(camelCase), and SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE (CONSTANT_VALUE). The exact
count of 4 catches a regression where the lexer splits an identifier
at an underscore or a case boundary.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Tokenize "myVar _privateVar camelCase CONSTANT_VALUE". Assert exactly
4 tokens.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- 4 identifiers -> 4 tokens
- Lexer splits "_privateVar" into "_" + "privateVar" -> count > 4
- Lexer rejects leading underscore -> count < 4
@End TestCases

Process called "test_lexer_identifiers" returns Integer:
    Note: Test C identifier tokenization

    proc print_string with "Testing C lexer (identifiers)..."
    proc print_newline

    Let source be proc create_string_literal with "myVar _privateVar camelCase CONSTANT_VALUE"
    Let lexer be proc create_lexer from Lexer with source
    proc tokenize from Lexer with lexer

    Let tokens be proc get_tokens from Lexer with lexer
    Let token_count be proc size from List with tokens

    Let expected_count be 4
    proc assert_equals with token_count, expected_count, "Identifier tokenization"

    proc destroy_lexer from Lexer with lexer
    proc print_string with "  ✓ Identifier lexer tests passed"
    proc print_newline

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Verifies both C comment forms (// line and /* ... */ block) are
skipped without producing tokens. Includes a newline inside the test
source so the line-comment terminator is exercised.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Tokenize "int x; // line comment\n/* block comment */ int y;".
Assert token count > 0 (expected ~6: int x ; int y ;) and that the
comment text itself never appears in the token stream.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- Input with both comment forms -> > 0 tokens, none containing
  comment text
- Lexer treats "//" as two divides -> count too high, contains text
- Lexer fails to find */ -> count == 0
@End TestCases

Process called "test_lexer_comments" returns Integer:
    Note: Test C comment handling

    proc print_string with "Testing C lexer (comments)..."
    proc print_newline

    Let source be proc create_string_literal with "int x; // line comment
/* block comment */ int y;"
    Let lexer be proc create_lexer from Lexer with source
    proc tokenize from Lexer with lexer

    Let tokens be proc get_tokens from Lexer with lexer
    Let token_count be proc size from List with tokens

    Note: Comments should be skipped, leaving only tokens for: int x ; int y ;
    Let _cm_ok be token_count is greater than 0
    proc assert_true with _cm_ok, "Comment skipping produces tokens"

    proc destroy_lexer from Lexer with lexer
    proc print_string with "  ✓ Comment lexer tests passed"
    proc print_newline

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Verifies the lexer handles three core preprocessor directives:
#include with angle-bracket header, #define for macros, and #ifdef
conditional compilation. The leading # must be recognized to switch
the lexer into directive mode.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Tokenize a multi-line source with #include, #define, #ifdef.
Assert token count > 0.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- Input with 3 directives -> > 0 tokens
- Lexer doesn't recognize "#" as directive opener -> count == 0
- Lexer rejects <stdio.h> angle-bracket form -> may still tokenize
  but produces wrong shape
@End TestCases

Process called "test_lexer_preprocessor" returns Integer:
    Note: Test C preprocessor directive tokenization

    proc print_string with "Testing C lexer (preprocessor)..."
    proc print_newline

    Let source be proc create_string_literal with "#include <stdio.h>
#define MAX 100
#ifdef DEBUG"
    Let lexer be proc create_lexer from Lexer with source
    proc tokenize from Lexer with lexer

    Let tokens be proc get_tokens from Lexer with lexer
    Let token_count be proc size from List with tokens

    Let _pp_ok be token_count is greater than 0
    proc assert_true with _pp_ok, "Preprocessor tokenization produces tokens"

    proc destroy_lexer from Lexer with lexer
    proc print_string with "  ✓ Preprocessor lexer tests passed"
    proc print_newline

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Parser Tests
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Verifies the parser handles binary arithmetic with precedence
("x + y * 2"). The "*" must bind tighter than "+" — a regression
where precedence is reversed would still produce an AST but with
the wrong structure (left-associated rather than precedence-aware).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Tokenize "x + y * 2", parse via parse_expression entry point. Assert
ast not null.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- Input "x + y * 2" -> non-null AST node, passed
- Parser returns null -> "Expression parsed" fails
@End TestCases

Process called "test_parser_expressions" returns Integer:
    Note: Test C expression parsing

    proc print_string with "Testing C parser (expressions)..."
    proc print_newline

    Let source be proc create_string_literal with "x + y * 2"
    Let lexer be proc create_lexer from Lexer with source
    proc tokenize from Lexer with lexer

    Let parser be proc create_parser from Parser with lexer
    Let ast be proc parse_expression from Parser with parser

    proc assert_not_null with ast, "Expression parsed"

    proc destroy_ast from Parser with ast
    proc destroy_parser from Parser with parser
    proc destroy_lexer from Lexer with lexer
    proc print_string with "  ✓ Expression parser tests passed"
    proc print_newline

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Verifies the parser handles an if-else with single-statement bodies
("if (x > 0) return x; else return -x;"). Exercises both branches
of the if-statement code path and the unary-minus prefix operator.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Tokenize the if-else line, parse via parse_statement. Assert ast not
null.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- Input "if (x > 0) return x; else return -x;" -> non-null AST, passed
- Parser fails on unary "-x" -> ast == 0
- Parser fails on else branch -> ast == 0
@End TestCases

Process called "test_parser_statements" returns Integer:
    Note: Test C statement parsing

    proc print_string with "Testing C parser (statements)..."
    proc print_newline

    Let source be proc create_string_literal with "if (x > 0) return x; else return -x;"
    Let lexer be proc create_lexer from Lexer with source
    proc tokenize from Lexer with lexer

    Let parser be proc create_parser from Parser with lexer
    Let ast be proc parse_statement from Parser with parser

    proc assert_not_null with ast, "Statement parsed"

    proc destroy_ast from Parser with ast
    proc destroy_parser from Parser with parser
    proc destroy_lexer from Lexer with lexer
    proc print_string with "  ✓ Statement parser tests passed"
    proc print_newline

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Verifies the parser handles a simple typed variable declaration with
initialization. This is the most common single-line C construct;
failure here breaks essentially all real C programs.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Tokenize "int x = 42;", parse via parse_declaration entry point.
Assert ast not null.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- Input "int x = 42;" -> non-null AST, passed
- Parser drops the initializer -> may succeed but semantics wrong
- Parser rejects "=" after declarator -> ast == 0
@End TestCases

Process called "test_parser_declarations" returns Integer:
    Note: Test C declaration parsing

    proc print_string with "Testing C parser (declarations)..."
    proc print_newline

    Let source be proc create_string_literal with "int x = 42;"
    Let lexer be proc create_lexer from Lexer with source
    proc tokenize from Lexer with lexer

    Let parser be proc create_parser from Parser with lexer
    Let ast be proc parse_declaration from Parser with parser

    proc assert_not_null with ast, "Declaration parsed"

    proc destroy_ast from Parser with ast
    proc destroy_parser from Parser with parser
    proc destroy_lexer from Lexer with lexer
    proc print_string with "  ✓ Declaration parser tests passed"
    proc print_newline

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Verifies the parser handles a complete function definition with
typed parameters, return type, and a body containing one return
statement. Exercises the parameter list parsing path that's distinct
from declaration-list parsing.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Tokenize "int add(int a, int b) { return a + b; }", parse via
parse_declaration. Assert ast not null.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- Input function with two parameters -> non-null AST, passed
- Parser drops the second parameter -> may still succeed (silent)
- Parser fails on function body -> ast == 0
@End TestCases

Process called "test_parser_functions" returns Integer:
    Note: Test C function parsing

    proc print_string with "Testing C parser (functions)..."
    proc print_newline

    Let source be proc create_string_literal with "int add(int a, int b) { return a + b; }"
    Let lexer be proc create_lexer from Lexer with source
    proc tokenize from Lexer with lexer

    Let parser be proc create_parser from Parser with lexer
    Let ast be proc parse_declaration from Parser with parser

    proc assert_not_null with ast, "Function parsed"

    proc destroy_ast from Parser with ast
    proc destroy_parser from Parser with parser
    proc destroy_lexer from Lexer with lexer
    proc print_string with "  ✓ Function parser tests passed"
    proc print_newline

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Verifies pointer ("int*"), array ("int arr[10]"), and scalar ("char c")
type forms in a single program. Exercises the type-specifier and
declarator-suffix parsing paths together.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Tokenize "int* ptr; int arr[10]; char c;", parse via parse_program
(top-level entry point). Assert ast not null.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- Input with pointer + array + scalar -> non-null program AST, passed
- Parser drops "[10]" array suffix -> may still succeed (silent)
- Parser fails on "*" pointer suffix -> ast == 0
@End TestCases

Process called "test_parser_types" returns Integer:
    Note: Test C type parsing

    proc print_string with "Testing C parser (types)..."
    proc print_newline

    Let source be proc create_string_literal with "int* ptr; int arr[10]; char c;"
    Let lexer be proc create_lexer from Lexer with source
    proc tokenize from Lexer with lexer

    Let parser be proc create_parser from Parser with lexer
    Let ast be proc parse_program from Parser with parser

    proc assert_not_null with ast, "Types parsed"

    proc destroy_ast from Parser with ast
    proc destroy_parser from Parser with parser
    proc destroy_lexer from Lexer with lexer
    proc print_string with "  ✓ Type parser tests passed"
    proc print_newline

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Semantic Analysis Tests
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Smoke test for the semantic analyzer: declare an int and a float and
verify analyze returns success. Catches a regression where the
analyzer rejects the basic numeric type set.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. Lex+parse "int x = 42; float y = 3.14;".
2. create_semantic_analyzer, then analyze(analyzer, ast) -> result.
3. Assert result == 1 (success).
4. Clean up analyzer, ast, parser, lexer.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- Input declares int and float with literals -> analyze returns 1
- Analyzer rejects float -> result == 0 -> "Semantic analysis succeeds" fails
@End TestCases

Process called "test_semantic_type_checking" returns Integer:
    Note: Test C type checking

    proc print_string with "Testing C semantic analysis (type checking)..."
    proc print_newline

    Let source be proc create_string_literal with "int x = 42; float y = 3.14;"
    Let lexer be proc create_lexer from Lexer with source
    proc tokenize from Lexer with lexer

    Let parser be proc create_parser from Parser with lexer
    Let ast be proc parse_program from Parser with parser

    Let analyzer be proc create_semantic_analyzer from Semantic
    Let result be proc analyze from Semantic with analyzer, ast

    proc assert_equals with result, 1, "Semantic analysis succeeds"

    proc destroy_semantic_analyzer from Semantic with analyzer
    proc destroy_ast from Parser with ast
    proc destroy_parser from Parser with parser
    proc destroy_lexer from Lexer with lexer
    proc print_string with "  ✓ Type checking tests passed"
    proc print_newline

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Verifies the analyzer handles variable shadowing (outer x = 10,
inner x = 20). The inner x must be resolved to the function-local
binding rather than the file-scope one — a regression where scope
push/pop is broken would either fail analysis or pick the wrong x.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. Lex+parse "int x = 10; int func() { int x = 20; return x; }".
2. analyze(analyzer, ast) -> result; assert == 1.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- Input with shadowed x -> analyze returns 1
- Analyzer rejects shadowing -> result == 0 -> "Scope resolution succeeds" fails
@End TestCases

Process called "test_semantic_scope_resolution" returns Integer:
    Note: Test C scope resolution

    proc print_string with "Testing C semantic analysis (scope resolution)..."
    proc print_newline

    Let source be proc create_string_literal with "int x = 10; int func() { int x = 20; return x; }"
    Let lexer be proc create_lexer from Lexer with source
    proc tokenize from Lexer with lexer

    Let parser be proc create_parser from Parser with lexer
    Let ast be proc parse_program from Parser with parser

    Let analyzer be proc create_semantic_analyzer from Semantic
    Let result be proc analyze from Semantic with analyzer, ast

    proc assert_equals with result, 1, "Scope resolution succeeds"

    proc destroy_semantic_analyzer from Semantic with analyzer
    proc destroy_ast from Parser with ast
    proc destroy_parser from Parser with parser
    proc destroy_lexer from Lexer with lexer
    proc print_string with "  ✓ Scope resolution tests passed"
    proc print_newline

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Translation Tests
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
End-to-end C-source-to-HIR check on the smallest meaningful program.
"int main() { return 0; }" exercises function definition, return
statement, and integer literal — the minimum viable C compilation
unit. The HIR structural check via assert_hir_has_type catches a
regression where the translator returns non-null but the resulting
HIR doesn't have the expected program type tag.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. Tokenize and parse_program "int main() { return 0; }".
2. translate_c_to_hir(ast) -> hir; assert not null.
3. assert_hir_has_type(hir, "c_program") -- exact type contract enforced.
4. Clean up.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- Input "int main() { return 0; }" -> HIR with type "c_program", passed
- Translator returns 0 -> "HIR created from C AST" fails
- HIR type != "c_program" -> assert_hir_has_type fires
@End TestCases

Process called "test_c_to_hir_translation" returns Integer:
    Note: Test C→HIR translation

    proc print_string with "Testing C→HIR translation..."
    proc print_newline

    Let source be proc create_string_literal with "int main() { return 0; }"
    Let lexer be proc create_lexer from Lexer with source
    proc tokenize from Lexer with lexer

    Let parser be proc create_parser from Parser with lexer
    Let ast be proc parse_program from Parser with parser

    Let hir be proc translate_c_to_hir from ToHIR with ast

    proc assert_not_null with hir, "HIR created from C AST"

    Note: Verify HIR structure
    proc assert_hir_has_type with hir, "c_program"

    proc destroy_ast from Parser with ast
    proc destroy_parser from Parser with parser
    proc destroy_lexer from Lexer with lexer
    proc print_string with "  ✓ C→HIR translation tests passed"
    proc print_newline

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Reverse direction: translate "int x = 42;" through to-HIR and then
back via from-HIR, asserting the emitter at least preserves the "int"
keyword token in its output. A weak signal but useful: an emitter
that drops all type info would fail here.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. Lex+parse "int x = 42;".
2. translate_c_to_hir(ast) -> hir.
3. generate_c_from_hir(hir) -> generated; assert not null.
4. string_contains(generated, "int") == 1.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- "int x = 42;" -> output contains "int", passed
- Emitter returns null -> "C generated from HIR" fails
- Emitter loses type token -> "Generated C contains 'int'" fails
@End TestCases

Process called "test_hir_to_c_generation" returns Integer:
    Note: Test HIR→C generation

    proc print_string with "Testing HIR→C generation..."
    proc print_newline

    Let source be proc create_string_literal with "int x = 42;"
    Let lexer be proc create_lexer from Lexer with source
    proc tokenize from Lexer with lexer

    Let parser be proc create_parser from Parser with lexer
    Let ast be proc parse_program from Parser with parser

    Let hir be proc translate_c_to_hir from ToHIR with ast
    Let generated be proc generate_c_from_hir from FromHIR with hir

    proc assert_not_null with generated, "C generated from HIR"

    Note: Verify generated output contains key elements
    Let contains_int be proc string_contains with generated, "int"
    proc assert_equals with contains_int, 1, "Generated C contains 'int'"

    proc destroy_ast from Parser with ast
    proc destroy_parser from Parser with parser
    proc destroy_lexer from Lexer with lexer
    proc print_string with "  ✓ HIR→C generation tests passed"
    proc print_newline

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Round-Trip Tests
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Smallest end-to-end round-trip: "int x = 42;" through tokenize ->
parse -> to-HIR -> from-HIR. Three string_contains assertions check
that the type ("int"), the identifier ("x"), and the literal ("42")
all survive both translation directions. If any of the three
elements is lost, the emitter has a regression.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. Lex+parse_program "int x = 42;".
2. translate_c_to_hir(ast) -> hir.
3. generate_c_from_hir(hir) -> generated; assert not null.
4. Three string_contains checks for "int", "x", "42"; assert each == 1.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- "int x = 42;" -> output contains "int", "x", "42", passed
- Emitter drops keyword -> "Round-trip contains 'int'" fails
- Emitter rewrites identifier -> "Round-trip contains 'x'" fails
- Emitter rewrites literal in different base -> "Round-trip contains '42'" fails
@End TestCases

Process called "test_round_trip_simple" returns Integer:
    Note: Test simple round-trip translation

    proc print_string with "Testing round-trip translation (simple)..."
    proc print_newline

    Let source be proc create_string_literal with "int x = 42;"
    Let lexer be proc create_lexer from Lexer with source
    proc tokenize from Lexer with lexer

    Let parser be proc create_parser from Parser with lexer
    Let ast be proc parse_program from Parser with parser

    Let hir be proc translate_c_to_hir from ToHIR with ast
    Let generated be proc generate_c_from_hir from FromHIR with hir

    proc assert_not_null with generated, "Round-trip completed"

    Note: Verify generated output contains key elements
    Let contains_int be proc string_contains with generated, "int"
    Let contains_x be proc string_contains with generated, "x"
    Let contains_42 be proc string_contains with generated, "42"

    proc assert_equals with contains_int, 1, "Round-trip contains 'int'"
    proc assert_equals with contains_x, 1, "Round-trip contains 'x'"
    proc assert_equals with contains_42, 1, "Round-trip contains '42'"

    proc destroy_ast from Parser with ast
    proc destroy_parser from Parser with parser
    proc destroy_lexer from Lexer with lexer
    proc print_string with "  ✓ Simple round-trip tests passed"
    proc print_newline

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Heavier end-to-end round-trip: a recursive factorial function with
parameters, conditional, and recursive call. Exercises function
definition + if-statement + return statement + function call all
in one program. The contains-checks for "factorial", "if", "return"
together signal that the emitter preserved the major structural
keywords and identifiers.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. Lex+parse_program the factorial function source.
2. translate_c_to_hir -> hir.
3. generate_c_from_hir -> generated; assert not null.
4. Three contains assertions for "factorial", "if", "return".
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- Recursive factorial -> output contains all three tokens, passed
- Emitter drops the function name -> "Round-trip contains 'factorial'" fails
- Emitter rewrites if as ternary -> "Round-trip contains 'if'" fails
- Emitter drops return statement -> "Round-trip contains 'return'" fails
@End TestCases

Process called "test_round_trip_complex" returns Integer:
    Note: Test complex round-trip translation

    proc print_string with "Testing round-trip translation (complex)..."
    proc print_newline

    Let source be proc create_string_literal with "int factorial(int n) {
    if (n is less than or equal to 1) {
        return 1;
    }
    return n multiplied by factorial(n minus 1);
}"
    Let lexer be proc create_lexer from Lexer with source
    proc tokenize from Lexer with lexer

    Let parser be proc create_parser from Parser with lexer
    Let ast be proc parse_program from Parser with parser

    Let hir be proc translate_c_to_hir from ToHIR with ast
    Let generated be proc generate_c_from_hir from FromHIR with hir

    proc assert_not_null with generated, "Complex round-trip completed"

    Note: Verify generated output contains key elements
    Let contains_factorial be proc string_contains with generated, "factorial"
    Let contains_if be proc string_contains with generated, "if"
    Let contains_return be proc string_contains with generated, "return"

    proc assert_equals with contains_factorial, 1, "Round-trip contains 'factorial'"
    proc assert_equals with contains_if, 1, "Round-trip contains 'if'"
    proc assert_equals with contains_return, 1, "Round-trip contains 'return'"

    proc destroy_ast from Parser with ast
    proc destroy_parser from Parser with parser
    proc destroy_lexer from Lexer with lexer
    proc print_string with "  ✓ Complex round-trip tests passed"
    proc print_newline

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Assertion Helpers
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Equality assertion that prints both operands on failure so a count
mismatch in a lexer test ("expected 10, got 9") tells the developer
exactly which keyword the lexer dropped without further bisection.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
If actual != expected, print "FAILED: <message> (expected <expected>,
got <actual>)" followed by a newline. Always returns 1 (test
continues on failure so the full set of mismatches is visible).
@End Implementation

Process called "assert_equals" takes actual as Integer, expected as Integer, message as String returns Integer:
    Note: Assert that two integers are equal

    If actual is not equal to expected:
        proc print_string with "FAILED: "
        proc print_string from message
        proc print_string with " (expected "
        proc print_integer from expected
        proc print_string with ", got "
        proc print_integer from actual
        proc print_string with ")"
        proc print_newline
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Boolean assertion for binary conditions (e.g. "count > 0"). Failure
prints just the message because the boolean itself isn't informative.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
If condition != 1, print "FAILED: <message>" followed by a newline.
Always returns 1.
@End Implementation

Process called "assert_true" takes condition as Integer, message as String returns Integer:
    Note: Assert that condition is true

    If condition is not equal to 1:
        proc print_string with "FAILED: "
        proc print_string from message
        proc print_newline
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Null-pointer assertion. Failure annotates "(value is null)" so the
log line distinguishes a null-return failure from a value-mismatch
failure.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
If value == 0, print "FAILED: <message> (value is null)" followed by
a newline. Always returns 1.
@End Implementation

Process called "assert_not_null" takes value as Integer, message as String returns Integer:
    Note: Assert that value is not equal to 0

    If value is equal to 0:
        proc print_string with "FAILED: "
        proc print_string from message
        proc print_string with " (value is null)"
        proc print_newline
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Composite HIR assertion: verifies the node exists AND that its "type"
attribute matches the expected string. Centralizes the HIR-shape
check so each translation test calls it as a one-liner.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. assert_not_null(hir, "HIR node exists").
2. HirNodes.get_attribute(hir, "type") -> node_type.
3. StringCore.string_equals(node_type, expected_type) -> types_match.
4. If != 1, Display "Type mismatch: expected <expected>" and return 0.
5. Otherwise return 1.
Note: returns 0 on mismatch (unlike the other asserts which always
return 1) so callers can short-circuit on hard failure.
@End Implementation

Process called "assert_hir_has_type" takes hir as Integer, expected_type as String returns Integer:
    Note: Assert that HIR has specific type

    Note: Verify HIR node is not equal to 0
    proc assert_not_null with hir, "HIR node exists"

    Note: Get HIR node type attribute
    Let node_type be proc get_attribute from HirNodes with hir, "type"

    Note: Compare with expected type
    Let types_match be proc string_equals from StringCore with node_type, expected_type
    If types_match is not equal to 1:
        Display "Type mismatch: expected " joined with expected_type
        Return 0
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: String Helpers
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Naive O(n*m) substring search used by the round-trip tests to verify
the emitter preserved key tokens. Reads needle bytes via raw memory
access while reading haystack bytes via StringCore so it can match
across different string representations.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. Empty needle -> return 1.
2. needle_len > haystack_len -> return 0.
3. Slide i from 0 to (haystack_len - needle_len). At each position,
   compare needle bytes; mismatch -> next i; all match -> return 1.
4. Exhausted -> return 0.
@End Implementation

Process called "string_contains" takes haystack as Integer, needle as String returns Integer:
    Note: Check if haystack contains needle substring

    Let haystack_len be proc string_length from StringCore with haystack
    Let needle_len be proc string_length from StringCore with needle

    If needle_len is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    If needle_len is greater than haystack_len:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let i be 0
    Let max_i be haystack_len minus needle_len

    While i is less than or equal to max_i:
        Let matches be 1
        Let j be 0

        While j is less than needle_len:
            Let h_char be proc string_char_at from StringCore with haystack, i plus j
            Let n_char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with needle, j

            If h_char is not equal to n_char:
                Set matches to 0
                Break
            End If

            Set j to j plus 1
        End While

        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Thin wrapper around StringCore.create_string_from_literal so test
code reads naturally instead of repeating the fully qualified call.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Forward to StringCore.create_string_from_literal(value) unchanged.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_string_literal" takes value as String returns Integer:
    Return proc create_string_from_literal from StringCore with value
End Process

